Although this is an old post with an accepted answer, I feel there is more to say. The other answers are of course right, that lambda expressions or method references don&#39;t have a well defined type without context. However, when applying them to arguments and maybe assigning the result to a variable, you are providing such a context, so that indeed you can define a static execute() function as you suggested. 

When you&#39;re not worried about your utility class &quot;MethodRefRunner&quot; getting a bit bigger, you can certainly at least cover the most common cases. The problem is that in principle you need to cover two infinite towers of cases. First are the cases with exactly one return type and an arbitrary number of arguments. Second tower are the cases with again an arbitrary number of arguments but no return type (so &quot;void&quot; which could be seen as special Type &quot;Void&quot;, but unfortunately Java refuses to accept lambda-expressions or method-references from one case for the other). 
The first tower is covered by `Supplier, Function, BiFunction, ...`
the second tower by `Runnable, Consumer, BiConsumer, ...`
In principle Function alone would be generic enough to cover all of these cases, but only in combination with currying, and there is no built-in currying in Java available. (a curried `BiFunction&lt;X,Y,Z&gt;` is a `Function&lt;X, Function&lt;Y, Z&gt;&gt;`).
So doing without currying, I&#39;d suggest the following:

    public class MethodRefRunner {
    static &lt;X&gt; X execute(Supplier&lt;X&gt; mref) {
		return mref.get();
	}
	static &lt;X, Y&gt; Y execute(Function&lt;X, Y&gt; mref, X arg) {
		return mref.apply(arg);
	}
	static &lt;X, Y, Z&gt; Z execute(BiFunction&lt;X, Y, Z&gt; mref, X arg1, Y arg2) {
		return mref.apply(arg1, arg2);
	}
	// ... (infinitely more needed for each number of arguments)


	// same infinite tower again with void return
	static void execute(Runnable mref) {
		mref.run();
	}

	static &lt;X&gt; void execute(Consumer&lt;X&gt; mref, X arg) {
		mref.accept(arg);
	}

	static &lt;X, Y&gt; void execute(BiConsumer&lt;X, Y&gt; mref, X arg1, Y arg2) {
		mref.accept(arg1, arg2);
	}
	// ... (infinitely more needed for each number of arguments)


	/* so here&#39;s the test, the example classes are defined below */
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		// initializing the environment
		A a = new A();
		B b = new B();
		ClassWithMethods object = new ClassWithMethods();


		// applying execute to method references
		execute(object::set, a);
		System.out.println(a == execute(object::get)); // true

		C c = execute(ClassWithMethods::staticMethod, a, b);
		System.out.println(c.equals(execute(object::method, b))); // true
		System.out.println(c.equals(execute(C::new, a, b))); // true

		// A last example with object-method reference for a non-specified object (C::equals instead of c::equals).
		// For some reason my compiler cannot deduce the types itself here, so one has to add a cast
		boolean isEqual = execute((BiFunction&lt;C, C, Boolean&gt;) C::equals, c, execute(C::new, a, b));
		System.out.println(isEqual); // true
	}

	/* in the following the example-classes used in the test above are defined */
	static class A {
	}
	static class B {
	}
	static class C {
		A a;
		B b;
		public C(A a, B b) {
			this.a = a;
			this.b = b;
		}

		public boolean equals(C other) {
			return a.equals(other.a) &amp;&amp; b.equals(other.b);
		}
	}
	static class ClassWithMethods {
		A a;

		public A get() {

			return this.a;
		}

		public void set(A a) {
			this.a = a;
		}

		public C method(B b) {

			return new C(this.a, b);
		}

		public static C staticMethod(A a, B b) {

			return new C(a, b);
		}
	}
    }

